This is a style question with several options.  Your issue is with the structure of your controller&#39;s mapping.

## Option 1

Create a single class to hold both items.
```java
@PostMapping(value = &quot;versions/service&quot;)
public ResponseEntity&lt;Version&gt; addNewVersionOfService(@RequestBody serviceVersion, @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) String serviceName){
    Version version = serviceVersion.getVersion();
    Service service = serviceVersion.getService();
    versionService.addNewVersionOfService(version, service, serviceName);
}
```

## Option 2
add one of them to the mapping as a path parameter.  Depending on the size of the object, version or service may be able to be set in the path.

```java
@PostMapping(&quot;{version}/service&quot;)
public ResponseEntity&lt;Version&gt; addNewVersionOfService(@PathVariable(&quot;version&quot;) Version version, @RequestBody Service service, @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) String serviceName){
    versionService.addNewVersionOfService(version, service, serviceName);
}
```

## Option 3:

Break your endpoint into two endpoints and leave the logic up to your consumer.  I don&#39;t necessarily recommend this if version and system are tightly coupled, but if it can be split out it may be useful for your REST consumer to be able to set their service and version separately.

```java
// create object 1 here
@PostMapping(&quot;versions&quot;)
public ResponseEntity&lt;Version&gt; addNewVersionOfService(@RequestBody Version version, @RequestBody Service service, @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) String serviceName){
    versionService.addNewVersionOfService(version, service, serviceName);
}

// create object 2 here.  throw error if object 1 doesn&#39;t exist
@PostMapping(&quot;versions/service&quot;)
public ResponseEntity&lt;Version&gt; addNewVersionOfService(@RequestBody Version version, @RequestBody Service service, @RequestParam(&quot;name&quot;) String serviceName){
    versionService.addNewVersionOfService(version, service, serviceName);
}
```

